body:
First, modify CMakeLists.txt to add jetson support

		-  set(CMAKE_CUDA_FLAGS "${CMAKE_CUDA_FLAGS} -gencode=arch=compute_50,code=sm_50") # M series
		+  set(CMAKE_CUDA_FLAGS "${CMAKE_CUDA_FLAGS} -gencode=arch=compute_53,code=sm_53") # Jetson support

Try the below build commandline instead (you can also add your numpy_version option if necessary):

./build.sh --config Release --update --build --build_wheel --use_tensorrt --cuda_home /usr/local/cuda --cudnn_home /usr/lib/aarch64-linux-gnu --tensorrt_home /usr/lib/aarch64-linux-gnu

Hi @jywu-msft thank your for the suggestion on how to attempt to fix this. I performed the steps you listed above and reinstalled onnxruntime, but python is still crashing when attempting to run the example. Although, now it seems to have changed from a bus error to a segmentation fault.

I attempted this on a different machine just to see what would happen and it is failing there as well. 

Machine stats: AWS p3.2xlarge w/ Tesla V100
OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Ubuntu 16.04 (based on deeplearning AMI)
ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): built from source
ONNX Runtime version: 0.4.0
Python version: 3.6.8
Visual Studio version (if applicable):
GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): 5.4.0
CUDA/cuDNN version: CUDA: 10.1 cuDNN: 7.5.0
GPU model and memory: Tesla V100
TensorRT version: 5.1.2.2

Build command was slightly different:

./build.sh --update --build --cudnn_home /usr/local/cuda/lib64 --cuda_home /usr/local/cuda --use_tensorrt --tensorrt_home /home/ubuntu/TensorRT-5.1.2.2 --build_wheel --config Release --numpy_version '1.16.1'

After installing the wheel file I ran the same example as before and still got the seg fault. 

Also, for some more info:

I am using the model found here when running the example code: https://github.com/onnx/models/tree/master/resnet50

Not sure if relevant/helpful, but when reading in the model, I get this output:

2019-05-09 19:45:21.930651033 [W:onnxruntime:Default, graph.cc:2208 CleanUnusedInitializers] gpu_0/imagenet1k_blobs_queue_f22e83c9-22cd-4a8b-a66d-113af6b832b4_0 exists in this graph's initializers but it is not used by any node
2019-05-09 19:45:42.538466587 [W:onnxruntime:InferenceSession, session_state_initializer.cc:508 SaveInputOutputNamesToNodeMapping] Graph input with name gpu_0/imagenet1k_blobs_queue_f22e83c9-22cd-4a8b-a66d-113af6b832b4_0 is not associated with a node.

if i'm reading it correctly, your 'hello world' model is resnet50.
that model expects input shape of [1,3,224,224] but you're using [3,4,5] ? 
(thought we should be doing input shape validation but maybe we aren't for python bindings.
default cpu returns error to some other validation failure and I think tensorrt seems to not do any validation and we encounter an invalid memory access.)

I tried this on jetson nano and it worked fine. can you try the same?

trttest@jetson1:~/resnet50$ python3
Python 3.6.7 (default, Oct 22 2018, 11:32:17)

@jywu-msft oh wow, you're absolutely right! I never changed the shape to match the model I was using and the low level faults were really throwing me off making me think it was something with the install itself. Thanks for the help!

closing this as it is resolved for the user.
will open another issue for avoiding low level failures in TensorRT provider.

labels.name: feature request
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
Currently only C API is available for ARM (Raspberry Pi for instance)

**Describe the solution you'd like**
A Python wrapper for onnxruntime on ARM devices.

body:
I had to add (not replace) the following to CMakeLists.txt at line [563](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/bfda9ca1c1e396411850e335f6c22ab1ffb90fe7/cmake/CMakeLists.txt#L563) to make sure cuda compiler is found by the build system:

`set(CMAKE_CUDA_COMPILER /usr/local/cuda/bin/nvcc)`


I am compiling onnxruntime natively on Jetson TX2.

issue.title: error: package directory 'onnxruntime/backend' does not exist on Jetson TX2 when installing from source

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
When I clone the onnxruntime git repository and install it from source with the command
"sudo python setup.py  install" I get the following error.

running install
running bdist_egg
running egg_info
creating onnxruntime.egg-info
writing top-level names to onnxruntime.egg-info/top_level.txt
writing requirements to onnxruntime.egg-info/requires.txt
writing dependency_links to onnxruntime.egg-info/dependency_links.txt
writing onnxruntime.egg-info/PKG-INFO
writing entry points to onnxruntime.egg-info/entry_points.txt
writing manifest file 'onnxruntime.egg-info/SOURCES.txt'
error: package directory 'onnxruntime/backend' does not exist

So this basically says that a directory is missing but i just cloned the master branch and did not edit anything.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Linux Ubuntu 16.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
- ONNX Runtime version: master branch and other releases
- Python version: Python 2.7 or Python 3.5 (both the same error)
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): GCC version 5.4.0
- CUDA/cuDNN version: CUDA 9.0
- GPU model and memory: NVIDIA Pascal (Jetson TX2 board)

**To Reproduce**
Describe steps/code to reproduce the behavior:
git clone https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime.git
cd onnxruntime
export ONNX_ML=1
sudo python setup.py install

Also doesn't work with git clone -b rel-0.2.0 https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime.git and other releases which support e.g. CUDA 9.1.
sudo python setup.py bdist_wheel gives the same error.

**Expected behavior**
The expected behavior would be that onnxruntime is installed from source with the setup.py script.

**Additional context**
The error appeared on a Jetson TX2 board.
